{'response': 'From childhood’s hour I have not been
Quite stitched into the world’s design;
A tapestry of might-have-been
Unfurled itself along my spine.
I saw in corners, odd and bright,
The trembling of a hidden flame;
I whispered to the silent night,
And called the wild winds by their name.
Others gathered warmth and song,
Their laughter spilled across the day;
But I, apart, would drift along
The edge where light and shadow play.
From childhood’s hour I have not been
A mimic of the crowd’s embrace;
Instead I’ve danced where few have seen—
The haunted halls of inner space.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;
When shadows fall and night is long,
No other voice but Thine I own,
No sweeter hope, no surer song.

In solitude, I seek Thy face,
A whisper in the silent air;
My spirit thirsts for Thy embrace,
And finds its peace in fervent prayer.

The world may tempt with fleeting charms,
Yet still my soul clings close to Thee;
In storm or calm, in joy’s alarms,
Thy steadfast love is liberty.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
My shelter, light, and guiding stone.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;
Upon the winds I carve Thy name.
In wilderness or crowded stone,
My longing heart remains the same.
No idol draws my spirit near,
No echo fills the silent hall;
But, in the hush, Thy voice I hear,
A whisper vast above it all.
The world may rage, the night may fall,
Yet in Thy light my soul has grown;
I see Thee, Lord, through joy and pall—
O God! Thou art my God alone.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;
In stillness, I call on Thee.
Through tangled woods and valleys grown,
Your love is my canopy.
The world may shimmer with false delight,
Yet none can satisfy my soul;
For in Your presence, day or night,
I find my longing whole.
No other refuge do I own,
No safer haven to be shown—
O God! Thou art my God alone;
My heart, my life, my cornerstone.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;
I seek Thee in the silent dawn,
Where whispers ride the waking breeze,
And hearts are hushed in reverent ease.
Before the golden light is sown,
My soul remembers Thee—my own;
In desert thirst, in shadowed night,
I lift my hands and find Thee bright.
No other voice so near, so true—
My hope, my joy, my life anew.
Thy steadfast love, a boundless sea;
O God, my God, abide with me.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'I was a grovelling creature once,
Low to the earth, eyes dull with fear;
My bones were heavy with ancient wants,
My voice unheard, my vision unclear.
But winds of change came whispering soft,
Lifting my chin from the cold, dark clay;
They taught my soul to rise aloft,
To seek the promise of day.
No longer do I scuttle and hide,
For I have tasted the sun and sky;
From dust and shadow, I learned my pride,
I was a grovelling creature—now I fly.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'People are happy in gardens of light,
Where laughter grows wild and dreams take to flight;
Sunbeams are woven through hours of play,
And troubles dissolve in the warmth of the day.
People are happy, their worries set free,
Dancing on air, as light as the sea;
The world is a canvas, their joy paints it bright,
People are happy in gardens of light.

But when night drapes the sky in its shimmering blue,
People are happy with hope shining through;
In whispers and wishes and stories retold,
People are happy, together and bold.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'I saw an old cottage of clay,
Nestled deep in the arms of the glen;
Its chimney breathed whispers of yesterday,
And its walls hummed the songs of lost men.
Wild roses curled ‘round its door,
Petals blushed by the dawn’s gentle hand;
Within, shadows danced on the floor,
Echoes of laughter, of dreams softly planned.
The roof sagged in time’s slow embrace,
Moss painting green memories past;
Yet in that small, humble place,
I felt the world’s heartbeat at last.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'My poem may be yours indeed,
Not merely mine, but also thine;
Each word a seed, each thought a bead,
Threaded on your silent line.
I set the verses free at dawn,
Unsure if you would ever see;
Yet now they live, and carry on
Inside your gentle memory.
So claim these words and make them new—
A tapestry that weaves us near;
For what I wrote with skies of blue,
You read beneath the stars, sincere.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Soldier, wake – the day is peeping
Through the cracks of silver dawn;
The fields, in mist, are softly sleeping,
But soon their silence will be gone.
Your boots await the morning dew,
Your heart, a drum, begins to pound;
The world awaits the brave and true,
As hope and fear alike resound.
Rise up, for light is gently creeping,
A golden call across the land;
Soldier, wake – the day is peeping,
And fate is pressing in your hand.

', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Soldier, wake—the day is peeping,
Golden rays upon your face;
Dreams dissolve while you are sleeping,
Duty stirs in silent grace.
Rise and meet the world’s becoming,
Leave your fears beside the bed;
Hear the distant morning drumming,
Feel the sun above your head.
Paths await your steady marching,
Fields are brushed in early hue;
Soldier, wake—the dawn is arching,
And the world is calling you.

', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Let the night sleep, do not stir the gentle dark—
Let quietude settle in every shadowed park.
The world has spun its stories, laughter, and regret;
Let peace descend where restless hearts forget.
Under the hush of indigo skies, let the hours creep,
Embracing the silence, let the night sleep.
Stars blink above, guardians of our dreams,
Tending the hush, soft as distant streams.
So close your eyes and let your worries keep;
Let the night sleep, let the night sleep.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'He spoke of Burns: men rude and rough,
Who tilled the fields and braved the storm;
With knuckles scarred and voices gruff,
Yet hearts beneath, a subtle form.
They raised their glasses to the skies,
And sang of hope, of love, of pain;
Their dreams, though simple, did arise
Like wildflowers after summer rain.
For in each jest and jostled jest,
A gentleness lay, pure and true;
He saw in them the poet’s test—
The soul that sang in every hue.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Shall I wasting in despair, when gardens wait to grow anew?
The winter’s chill may linger, but the sun will soon break through.
Each withered leaf, each silent tear, is compost for the soul;
From broken earth, the roots appear and push toward their goal.
I will not count the hours lost, nor mourn what might have been;
The future calls, its fingers crossed, for all I’ve yet to win.
Despair may visit for a night, but hope will take the throne;
With every dawn’s returning light, I rise and walk alone.
For wasting in despair, I see, would keep me from the spring;
So let me shape my destiny and find the joy I bring.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Shall I wasting in despair, when fields lie fallow under moon,
And every hope’s a withered prayer, surrendered all too soon?
Yet in the hush between the stars, a trembling promise weaves its thread,
Reminding me of who we are, and dreams that bloom though seasons fled.

Let not my spirit fold in grief, nor let my song dissolve in night;
For every heartache finds relief, and darkness yields to gentle light.
So, let me gather strength anew, and face the dawn’s uncertain glare;
For though I’ve stumbled, as we do, I shan’t be wasting in despair.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Shall I wasting in despair, counting tears that never dry?
Shall I let the world unravel, or find the strength to try?
The garden waits with open arms, the dawn with gentle hand;
If sorrow’s tide would pull me down, I’ll plant my feet in sand.

The willow weeps for moments lost, but hope is not a ghost;
It flickers in the quiet hours when I need it most.
So no, I won’t be wasting, nor will I yield to fear;
For even in my darkest days, I’ll hold the light near.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Shall I wasting in despair, as love’s bright embers fade,
And watch the world in muted tones, all color slowly grayed?
Or shall I, undaunted, seek the sunrise through the tears,
And gather up the scattered hopes that linger from the years?

There’s music in the silence, a lesson in the ache;
A thousand seeds of courage lie dormant for my sake.
Despair may be a visitor, but hope will hold me fast—
I’ll build a bridge from heartbreak to futures unsurpassed.
So let me not be wasted, a shadow lost to care;
I’ll write my song of healing, and rise from deep despair.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'She lies alone upon her bed,
A hush of midnight cloaks her room;
Moonlight carves a silver thread
Across the silence, soft as bloom.
She dreams of voices, laughter, light,
Of distant places, distant years;
Her pillow gathers gentle night,
And soaks the salt of hidden tears.
Yet in her solitude, she grows—
A quiet strength beneath the ache;
The petals close, but soon, who knows?
At dawn, a heart may reawake.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'She lies alone upon her bed,
Shadows dance across the floor;
Her thoughts, like feathers, softly spread,
To places she’s not been before.
The hush of night, a velvet shroud,
Enfolds her dreams in silent grace;
While echoes linger, never loud,
Of laughter lost in time and space.
Yet in the dark, she finds a spark,
A tiny flame she keeps within;
For even as the world grows stark,
She knows the dawn will soon begin.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'She lies alone upon her bed,
A gentle sigh escapes her lips;
The world has spun, the day has fled,
Night’s velvet curtain softly slips.
The quiet hum of distant cars,
A lullaby for restless minds;
She gazes out to scattered stars,
And all her hope, the darkness binds.
Yet in this private, sacred space,
She learns to trust her inner voice;
In solitude, she finds her grace,
And in the silence, makes her choice.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'She lies alone upon her bed,
A tapestry of dreams unfurls;
With silent longing, softly led
Through corridors of secret worlds.
The walls recall her laughter’s trace,
The air still holds a lover’s scent;
Yet solitude, a warm embrace,
Becomes her gentle, firmament.
She weaves her wishes in the night,
With every breath, a whispered plea;
From loneliness, she carves delight,
And lets her spirit wander free.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': "Homer poured, in thousand wrote,
His verses sailed on wine-dark seas;
He sowed the stars with every note,
And caught the dawn upon the breeze.
His words were ships that dared to roam,
Past siren calls and tempest's wrath;
Odysseus wandered far from home,
Yet Homer guided every path.
A thousand pens, a thousand dreams,
All gathered in a single hand;
He spun the world from golden streams,
And shaped our hearts to understand.

", 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Beneath the soot and humble guise,
A spark of radiance softly lies;
Cinderella is not the shoe,
But something shining, pure, and true.
No glass or gown can quite define
The beauty born from heart and mind;
For every ash upon her skin
Conceals the glow that burns within.
So let the world look past the seam—
To find the soul, the hope, the dream;
Cinderella, more than face or art,
Is the gentle strength of a loving heart.

', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Please spare me your secrets, I beg you tonight;
Let mystery linger and shadows take flight.
The words left unspoken are gentle and kind,
More soothing than truths that unravel the mind.

What comfort in silence, what peace in the dark,
When questions unanswered leave only a mark.
We’re safer, perhaps, with a little unknown,
Protected by quiet and secrets our own.

So keep what you carry, let silence remain;
I cherish the hush more than any refrain.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Please spare me your secrets, the cracks in your smile,
The words you withhold as you linger awhile.
Not every confession demands to be heard;
Some feelings are safer when left undisturbed.

Let silence be shelter, a balm for the soul;
The weight of your burdens is not mine to hold.
I offer you presence, not judgment or blame—
A warmth in the quiet, unspoken by name.

So keep what you must, let the rest drift away;
No need for the darkness to color our day.
Please spare me your secrets, let peace be our thread—
Some things are best cherished by staying unsaid.', 'probability': 1.0}
